This PR makes it so that when creating a subprocess on windows no console window is displayed","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/b3139156e3df77ad8909d321c66d0be72e82f666"},{"sha":"ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Fix for ROCm CSB breakage - 210329

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d"},{"sha":"95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec"},{"sha":"7a2f8ffed7ddf9efe0acef69a95ecab7adbb562a","author":{"name":"Rajeshwar Reddy T","email":"81ddf3010ddb2346b6246603d3a55c487a2e7769@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/7a2f8ffed7ddf9efe0acef69a95ecab7adbb562a"},{"sha":"5bf089dc4d5e3b045252f6a7f340caf778aa42e0","author":{"name":"Scott Zhu","email":"65d81eb4203ec9a5a8b298abc5184127125bc9fe@google.com"},"message":"Expose saved_model.SavedModelBuilder as the internal API

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/42ef2c5036f5131fbabf7389ac7efa049cd63cd2"},{"sha":"2834f842ee25c081abad0dc1473dd7c65ce94cb8","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use containerd's apparmor package to detect if apparmor can be used

The runc/libcontainer apparmor package on master no longer checks if apparmor_parser
is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

While those checks are not relevant to runc (as it doesn't load the profile), these
checks _are_ relevant to us (and containerd). So switching to use the containerd
apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"938dc5527a2620c2a5e598b4e46cb1e963e2d257","author":{"name":"Scott Zhu","email":"65d81eb4203ec9a5a8b298abc5184127125bc9fe@google.com"},"message":"Expose saved_model.parse_saved_model as internal API

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d"},{"sha":"95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec"},{"sha":"c309302b3833c4bfacfc918246fde2769e6a9345","author":{"name":"Dan Moldovan","email":"02bd3f004a63c78990e4cfa97922eaaaa6d78ea5@google.com"},"message":"Experimental prototype for FullType infrastructure for GraphDef.

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})

Expected: true
```

For ROCm 4.0 and prior, hipfft was a header-only "library" that was shipped along with the rocfft library. ROCm TF code uses the hipfft APIs defined in the "hipfft.h" header file, which was part of the package for rocfft library. ROCm TF would dynamically load the "rocfft" library at runtime.

From ROCm 4.1 onwards, it seems hipfft is a separate library from rocfft, and ROCm TF needs to use the "hipfft" library insteaf of the "rocfft" library. Specifcally, ROCm TF needs to
* pick up the "hipfft.h" header from the hipfft install area (instead of the rocfft install area).
* dynamically load the the "hipfft" library instead of the "rocfft" library
This commit has the two above changes

This change is required because without this change, the unit-tests that called the hipfft API ( `hipfftSetWorkArea` ) were failing when run with ROCm 4.1 (and without the changes in this commit).

ROCm TF continues to build (with ROCm 4.1) without the changes in this commit, because the old "hipfft.h" file in the rocfft install area is still present (do not know whether that is by design or accident)

unit-tests known to call the `hipfftSetWorkArea` API

is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

[{"sha":"03b4375f913feba04bfa0c5d5924ae91ee1ffeb7","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/03b4375f913feba04bfa0c5d5924ae91ee1ffeb7"}]

full diff: https://github.com/containerd/containerd/compare/fbf1a72de7da110187b7d3dace433914b9beca10...55eda46b22f985cde99b599e469ff9c13994bf68

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/42ef2c5036f5131fbabf7389ac7efa049cd63cd2"},{"sha":"2834f842ee25c081abad0dc1473dd7c65ce94cb8","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"Use containerd's apparmor package to detect if apparmor can be used

The runc/libcontainer apparmor package on master no longer checks if apparmor_parser
is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

While those checks are not relevant to runc (as it doesn't load the profile), these
checks _are_ relevant to us (and containerd). So switching to use the containerd
apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d"},{"sha":"95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec"},{"sha":"38f85b281a57f3d47d55b07837b1b39b2027aff1","author":{"name":"Edward Loper","email":"4e70de59cddd527517e9ce09eb7412beeffcbd1a@google.com"},"message":"For StructTensors with no fields: include `nrows` and `row_partitions` in return value for StructuredTensorSpec._to_components.

apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 364451977
Change-Id: Ib5ef2e6067a601726d7c2ce787b7357049850f37","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/asus4/tensorflow/commits/0979d2adf2d92566960eba4c3ef27e6a7cf5b8bc"},{"sha":"550a60b9823f7c0f0f3bbc61931e5e64199e9985","author":{"name":"Jaesung Chung","email":"935e11c5b050a3a02c4f0e08de55daf431709deb@google.com"},"message":"Introduce a new experimental and private converter flag to put user's TFLite
custom op libraries into calibrator.

When TFLite custom ops were enabled in a model, the calibrator will always be
broken at finding TFLite custom op handlers since the calibration_wrapper just
uses the TFLite builtin op resolver always.

By using the new experimental and private flag,
converter.target_spec._experimental_custom_op_registerers,
users will enable post training quantization with calibrations for the models
that contain user provided TFLite custom op libraries.

Usage:

converter = tf.lite.TFLiteConverter.from_keras_model(model)
converter.optimizations = [lite.Optimize.DEFAULT]
converter.representative_dataset = calibration_gen
converter.allow_custom_ops = True
converter.target_spec._experimental_custom_op_registerers = [
  "AddHashTableOps", "AddStringOps"
]

Fix issue 41762

Cherry-pick "drivers: btrfs: Allow unprivileged user to delete subvolumes" from containers/storage
https://github.com/containers/storage/pull/508/commits/831e32b6bdcb530acc4c1cb9059d3c6dba14208c

> In btrfs, subvolume can be deleted by IOC_SNAP_DESTROY ioctl but there
> is one catch: unprivileged IOC_SNAP_DESTROY call is restricted by default.
>
> This is because IOC_SNAP_DESTROY only performs permission checks on
> the top directory(subvolume) and unprivileged user might delete dirs/files
> which cannot be deleted otherwise. This restriction can be relaxed if
> user_subvol_rm_allowed mount option is used.
>
> Although the above ioctl had been the only way to delete a subvolume,
> btrfs now allows deletion of subvolume just like regular directory
> (i.e. rmdir sycall) since kernel 4.18.
>
> So if we fail to cleanup subvolume in subvolDelete(), just fallback to
> system.EnsureRmoveall() to try to cleanup subvolumes again.
> (Note: quota needs privilege, so if quota is enabled we do not fallback)
>
> This fix will allow non-privileged container works with btrfs backend.

Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Fix for ROCm CSB breakage - 210329

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d"},{"sha":"95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec"},{"sha":"eded08c503d954d63c8ad97633663c54be2de294","author":{"name":"Hanhan Wang","email":"17db91a825a40156b2c20ef2022824cbafd12aac@google.com"},"message":"[NFC] Fix a typo in ScalarLimit comments.

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations

artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

DevTools was built with a fork of an early idea for how Suspense cache might work. This idea is incompatible with newer APIs like `useTransition` which unfortunately prevented me from making certain UX improvements. This PR swaps out the primary usage of this cache (there are a few) in favor of the newer `unstable_getCacheForType` and `unstable_useCacheRefresh` APIs. We can go back and update the others in follow up PRs.

### Messaging changes

I've refactored the way the frontend loads component props/state/etc to hopefully make it better match the Suspense+cache model. Doing this gave up some of the small optimizations I'd added but hopefully the actual performance impact of that is minor and the overall ergonomic improvements of working with the cache API make this worth it.

The backend no longer remembers inspected paths. Instead, the frontend sends them every time and the backend sends a response with those paths. I've also added a new "force" parameter that the frontend can use to tell the backend to send a response even if the component hasn't rendered since the last time it asked. (This is used to get data for newly inspected paths.)

_Initial inspection..._
```
front |                                                      | back
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:true) ---------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes with no updates..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:false) --------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (no-change) -- |
```
_User clicks to expand a path, aka hydrate..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:true) ----> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes during which there is an update..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:false) ---> |
      | <----------------- "inspectedElement" (full-data) -- |
```

### Clear errors/warnings transition
Previously this meant there would be a delay after clicking the "clear" button. The UX after this change is much improved.

### Hydrating paths transition
I also added a transition to hydration (expanding "dehyrated" paths).

### Better error boundaries
I also added a lower-level error boundary in case the new suspense operation ever failed. It provides a better "retry" mechanism (select a new element) so DevTools doesn't become entirely useful. Here I'm intentionally causing an error every time I select an element.

### Improved snapshot tests
I also migrated several of the existing snapshot tests to use inline snapshots and added a new serializer for dehydrated props. Inline snapshots are easier to verify and maintain and the new serializer means dehydrated props will be formatted in a way that makes sense rather than being empty (in external snapshots) or super verbose (default inline snapshot format).","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe"},{"sha":"ba9582da27481677cdac2dd000a438147a5df88e","author":{"name":"ChenLei","email":"2078e632128f17c4aa4e413d134a36c7418bccff@qq.com"},"message":"[devtools] Fix can't expand prop value in some scenario (#20534)

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

The runc/libcontainer apparmor package on master no longer checks if apparmor_parser
is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

While those checks are not relevant to runc (as it doesn't load the profile), these
checks _are_ relevant to us (and containerd). So switching to use the containerd
apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

The runc/libcontainer apparmor package on master no longer checks if apparmor_parser
is enabled, or if we are running docker-in-docker.

While those checks are not relevant to runc (as it doesn't load the profile), these
checks _are_ relevant to us (and containerd). So switching to use the containerd
apparmor package, which does include the needed checks.

One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```

Expected: true
```

This PR makes it so that when creating a subprocess on windows no console window is displayed","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/b3139156e3df77ad8909d321c66d0be72e82f666"},{"sha":"ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Fix for ROCm CSB breakage - 210329

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d"},{"sha":"95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec"},{"sha":"7a2f8ffed7ddf9efe0acef69a95ecab7adbb562a","author":{"name":"Rajeshwar Reddy T","email":"81ddf3010ddb2346b6246603d3a55c487a2e7769@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/7a2f8ffed7ddf9efe0acef69a95ecab7adbb562a"},{"sha":"5bf089dc4d5e3b045252f6a7f340caf778aa42e0","author":{"name":"Scott Zhu","email":"65d81eb4203ec9a5a8b298abc5184127125bc9fe@google.com"},"message":"Expose saved_model.SavedModelBuilder as the internal API

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/119e787fe5cfcfa6d4659da9b83bbb93f55dc32d"},{"sha":"95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec","author":{"name":"Yasir Modak","email":"520e7eac3b4564c444401075525ae8f465a82106@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update bot_config.yml","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/95b34b42b60b85117ff61a576ea36453051a4bec"},{"sha":"04c64e8119c17ffc162d4e7087e32a208c13aca8","author":{"name":"Yuanzhong Xu","email":"4a8be3b63a1468bbe5756287a5d3023353bf211f@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:SPMD] Avoid masking if pad value is zero and no uneven partitioning

[{"sha":"8973f7141829e98cb596bd8d3a6b800d2c199473","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Fix: Don't flush discrete at end of batchedUpdates

The outermost `batchedUpdates` call flushes pending sync updates at the
end. This was intended for legacy sync mode, but it also happens to
flush discrete updates in concurrent mode.

Instead, we should only flush sync updates at the end of
`batchedUpdates` for legacy roots. Discrete sync updates can wait to
flush in the microtask.

`discreteUpdates` has the same issue, which is how I originally noticed
this, but I'll change that one in a separate commit since it requires
updating a few (no longer relevant) internal tests.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/8973f7141829e98cb596bd8d3a6b800d2c199473"}]

This PR makes it so that when creating a subprocess on windows no console window is displayed","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/b3139156e3df77ad8909d321c66d0be72e82f666"},{"sha":"ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Fix for ROCm CSB breakage - 210329

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))

The test has race condition, which is addressed by the patch.

The race is next:

    Master thread is calling execute (effectively blocked, waiting for
callback to be called)
    "Async" thread picks up the callback
    Call the callback
    Then sets the variables in test
    After call back is called, master thread is unblocked and may check
the variables (set in point 4 by the "async" thread) earlier then they
actually changed

Changes:

    callback should be called as the last step (after flag variables are
    set), as it effectively unblock the master thread

fixes #18974","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/opencv/opencv/commits/eb6d8e6af233e0c021bfae4e04f36b2b844157a8"},{"sha":"6f5af6eb42e2aef207d248882bd3fec2e3882208","author":{"name":"Alexander Alekhin","email":"68add3c7f0912f500ebe6e9539930fd1bb229c72@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #18982 from anton-potapov:sole_tbb_executor_async_test","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/opencv/opencv/commits/6f5af6eb42e2aef207d248882bd3fec2e3882208"},{"sha":"fc54853d44fae538a54b7d27f219bd24a57e0f4c","author":{"name":"Alexander Alekhin","email":"68add3c7f0912f500ebe6e9539930fd1bb229c72@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #18972 from Rightpoint:task/colejd/prevent-existing-xcframework-error","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/opencv/opencv/commits/fc54853d44fae538a54b7d27f219bd24a57e0f4c"}]

The following commit breaks the XLA unit-testcases on the ROCm platform

https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/cb3e0b2bb94ec414d709970181259e2f2cbba769#diff-3916e937a690715a62df34b7dae19bbdd92d7c79b9d6712ba3605b8d208c8a7fR7

The above commit updates the LLVM pointer, which in turn picks a lot of changes in the AMDGPU backend implementation in LLVM. One of those changes is to use code-object-v4, by default, for the generated HSACOs (AMDGPU binaries). This is okay if you also use the corresponding HIP runtime, which is ROCm 4.1 or higher. But with ROCm 4.0.1 or older, the newer HSACO files do not get loaded properly by the older HIP runtime, resulting in errors like the following error

```
tensorflow/compiler/xla/service/gpu/tests/reduction_layout_normalizer_test.cc:62: Failure
Value of: RunAndCompare(hlo_text, ErrorSpec{1e-5, 1e-5})
  Actual: false (Internal: Failed to load HSACO: hipError_t(303))
Expected: true
```

This commit fixes the issue by changing the default code object version to v3, when TF is built with ROCm 4.0.1 or older.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/ae656b503b7c415115bd8f62435af067dfe555d8"},{"sha":"913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding support for enbale_ftz flag (flush denormals to zero) in the LLVM backend for AMDGPUs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/913e96496fd4e27387b64a3472569dc0d7d75da4"},{"sha":"5fe53028a58e3b51fef1c3456f04e90e3bab5e39","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #48419 from ROCmSoftwarePlatform:google_upstream_rocm_fixes_210408
